sec.p:
In the first period, A and B bargain over a transfer of the player. Two aspects of the outcome of this bargaining process are easy to determine. First, it is rather obvious that the player is always transferred to B. Again, this happens because the value of the player to club B over both periods is higher than to club A (regardless of whether the player is transferred to C in t = 2). Second, the functional form of the sell-on fee f
2(fC
) does not depend on which of the two clubs makes the take-it-or-leave-it offer. If a club is allowed to make the offer, it pursues two goals. On one hand, it wants to maximize the size of the surplus that can be allocated between the club and the other club. On the other hand, it wants to secure a high share of this surplus. While f
1 can only be used for distribution, f
2(fC
) affects behavior in the second period and hence also affects the size of the surplus in t = 1. Accordingly, it is optimal for each club to determine f
2(fC
) such as to maximize the size of the surplus and to use f
1 to allocate it in the club’s best possible way.
